  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">EA07/2021 Caritas Rohingya and Host Community Response in Bangladesh</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The COVID-19 pandemic presented a huge risk to Rohingya refugees in 2020, and severely constrained humanitarian response. Bangladesh reported its first confirmed COVID-19 case on March 8; the first confirmed case was found in Cox&apos;s Bazar on 24 March, and the first COVID-related death on 30 April. It was feared that the Rohingya refugee camps at Cox&apos;s Bazar would be the ideal breeding ground for coronavirus; The GoB (Government of Bangladesh) along with the UN and other humanitarian partners working in the refugee camps have made significant efforts to reduce the risk of COVID-19 spreading further in the camps in Cox&#x2019;s Bazar, and scaled up testing and emergency treatments centers in anticipation of large caseloads. Fortunately, these caseloads have not materialized: As of 31 December 2020, Bangladesh had reported 513,510, confirmed COVID-19 cases, 5,407 of which had been identified in Cox&#x2019;s Bazar District, including 367 Rohingya refugees.   

Caritas Bangladesh have launched EA07/2021, which has a covid-19 cross-cutting theme (focused on sensitization, awareness raising and WASH facilities) in addition to shelter and protection activities.</narrative>
  </description>
